03:07.771 --> 03:10.941
<i>♪ Pretty soon
I grew accustomed ♪</i>

03:11.024 --> 03:15.028
<i>♪ To her warm and sunny way ♪</i>

03:17.823 --> 03:20.742
<i>♪ Pretty soon I would forget ♪</i>

03:20.826 --> 03:23.912
<i>♪ About those frigid
winter days ♪</i>

03:26.790 --> 03:27.874
<i>♪ If you just stay true... ♪</i>

03:27.958 --> 03:31.336
Thank God you're here.

03:31.420 --> 03:33.797
Your grandfather's been
driving me bonkers.

03:35.132 --> 03:37.092
‐Noah.
‐Margaret.

03:37.175 --> 03:38.927
‐Where's Helen?
‐Oh, I told you, Grandma.

03:39.010 --> 03:40.720
She couldn't come.
She had to work.

03:40.804 --> 03:42.097
Well, that's just disgusting.

03:42.180 --> 03:43.932
I don't think so.

03:44.015 --> 03:44.850
Well, of course it is.

03:44.933 --> 03:46.726
This is your wedding.

03:46.810 --> 03:49.438
What could be more important
than your wedding, Whitney?

03:49.521 --> 03:51.648
I swear I brought
your mother up better than that.

03:51.731 --> 03:53.859
I really did.

03:53.942 --> 03:56.069
Oh, well.
She's a lost cause.

03:56.153 --> 03:58.738
You're my only hope
for happiness now.

03:58.822 --> 04:00.282
Ugh. Come upstairs.

04:00.365 --> 04:02.993
I've laid out
all the bridal magazines.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.953
Noah, take Whitney's things
to the blue room.

04:05.036 --> 04:06.204
You're in the basement.

04:06.288 --> 04:08.248
Oh, and see if you can
find Bruce.

04:08.331 --> 04:10.083
He'd be thrilled to see you.

04:15.881 --> 04:19.843
Hey. Hey, Bruce.

04:19.926 --> 04:22.262
‐Hi.
‐H‐Hello.

04:24.890 --> 04:26.349
Who are you?

04:26.433 --> 04:29.186
Uh, Noah.

04:30.353 --> 04:31.938
Noah. N‐Noah Solloway?

04:32.022 --> 04:34.274
‐I'm your ex‐‐
‐Oh, oh. Yes, of course.

04:34.357 --> 04:34.775
I'm so sorry.

04:34.858 --> 04:36.985
Uh, Bruce Butler.

04:37.068 --> 04:39.488
Margaret told me
you were coming.

04:39.571 --> 04:41.156
The writer. Uh...

04:41.239 --> 04:42.866
She says you've published
multiple books.

04:42.949 --> 04:44.367
That's right, yeah.

04:44.451 --> 04:46.495
Wow, that's impressive.

04:46.578 --> 04:49.664
Uh, you know,
there's a great expression.

04:49.748 --> 04:51.875
Uh...

04:51.958 --> 04:55.504
"No one has one book
in him, but..."

04:55.587 --> 04:57.172
Um. It's, uh...

04:57.255 --> 04:59.508
I think it's,
"Everyone has one book in them.

04:59.591 --> 05:01.510
Almost nobody has two."

05:02.928 --> 05:06.723
Oh. Uh... That's not very nice.

05:06.807 --> 05:09.684
Uh, you know,
I always wanted to be a writer.

05:09.768 --> 05:13.271
But there never seemed
to be enough hours in the day.

05:13.355 --> 05:14.606
Yeah...

05:14.689 --> 05:17.150
Are you hungry?
I was craving some, uh,

05:17.234 --> 05:19.319
some of these, uh...

05:19.402 --> 05:20.695
‐ some of these...
‐ Here.

05:20.779 --> 05:22.239
Bruce, let‐let me
make those for you.

05:22.322 --> 05:23.907
No. No, no, you're our guest.

05:23.990 --> 05:27.160
You know... No, no.
You... have‐have some coffee.

05:27.244 --> 05:31.414
Uh, uh, I have no idea
how to use that machine.

05:31.498 --> 05:33.166
Sure, I'll make some.

05:33.250 --> 05:37.546
Um, are you, uh, you married?

05:39.422 --> 05:42.551
Uh, no. Divorced.

05:42.634 --> 05:44.427
Twice, actually.

05:44.511 --> 05:47.514
Well, that's probably why
you have so much time to write.

05:47.597 --> 05:50.559
I'm more of
a family man, myself.

05:50.976 --> 05:52.060
Bruce, no.

05:52.143 --> 05:54.145
‐ Oh...
‐Oh, Jesus.

05:56.815 --> 05:57.615
- ‐It's okay.
- ‐

05:57.649 --> 06:00.193
‐No...
‐I just, I just wanted to‐‐

06:00.277 --> 06:02.445
It's‐it's all right,
it's all right. Shh, shh.

06:02.529 --> 06:06.825
We're trying
to set boundaries for Bruce.

06:06.908 --> 06:07.708
Some new expectations.

06:07.784 --> 06:09.494
While you're here,
I'd appreciate it

06:09.578 --> 06:10.412
if you could help with that.

06:10.495 --> 06:12.622
I'm sorry.
I didn't... I didn't know.

06:12.706 --> 06:13.915
Well, now you do.

06:16.001 --> 06:17.294
Hi.

06:17.377 --> 06:19.796
Ah.
What are you doing here?

06:19.880 --> 06:23.717
‐I'm getting married.
‐What? To this fellow?

06:23.800 --> 06:26.261
Why, Helly‐Belly,
that's fantastic.

06:26.344 --> 06:28.013
Does this mean that
you've finally broken up

06:28.096 --> 06:29.931
with that kid from Pennsylvania?

06:30.015 --> 06:30.974
The‐the one that
was practically a mute?

06:31.057 --> 06:32.893
Bruce, t‐this is Whitney.

06:32.976 --> 06:36.187
Helen is your daughter.
This is your granddaughter.

06:36.271 --> 06:38.106
G‐Granddaughter?

06:38.189 --> 06:39.941
I can't do this anymore.

06:40.025 --> 06:40.901
It's okay.
Margaret, it's okay.

06:40.984 --> 06:42.485
Let's‐let's focus
on the wedding. Uh...

06:42.569 --> 06:44.362
Whitney has this huge agenda
for us,

06:44.446 --> 06:46.323
and, uh, she needs your help.

06:46.406 --> 06:47.866
Uh, that's right, Grandma.

06:47.949 --> 06:50.493
Um, I need to decide
on a florist.

06:50.577 --> 06:51.953
I've narrowed it down to three,

06:52.037 --> 06:53.455
but I'm sure
you'll have an opinion.

06:53.538 --> 06:56.124
Um, I need to
figure out a caterer.

06:56.207 --> 06:58.043
I wanted to find somebody
who could do vegan options.

06:58.126 --> 06:59.044
I don't know if you know
anybody.

06:59.127 --> 07:01.212
And, um... Oh, well,
we already got a tent.

07:01.296 --> 07:03.214
Oh, that reminds me.

07:03.298 --> 07:04.549
The bill for the tent came.

07:06.926 --> 07:08.803
Margaret, I'm...

07:08.887 --> 07:09.846
I thought I was doing
the catering,

07:09.929 --> 07:12.349
and you and Bruce were
gonna pay for the tent.

07:12.432 --> 07:15.727
Noah, we can't pay for this.
It's $20,000.

07:16.478 --> 07:18.647
We don't have any money.

07:18.730 --> 07:20.857
And whose fault
is that, Marie Antoinette?

07:22.942 --> 07:25.570
Whitney,
I just had a splendid idea.

07:25.654 --> 07:29.407
Why don't I call Dean
at our tennis club?

07:29.491 --> 07:30.200
They do a marvelous brunch.

07:30.283 --> 07:32.035
And if we do
the wedding reception

07:32.118 --> 07:34.704
outside of peak hours,

07:34.788 --> 07:36.331
I'm sure we can get a discount

07:36.414 --> 07:37.749
on the cabana.

07:37.832 --> 07:39.000
They have a waffle station

07:39.084 --> 07:42.170
and a make‐your‐own‐omelette
bar.

07:42.253 --> 07:44.089
Excuse me, please.

07:47.634 --> 07:51.179
Okay, M‐Margaret, the‐the
wedding is happening here.

07:51.262 --> 07:53.348
Okay? So, if you want
to help,

07:53.431 --> 07:56.851
help us figure out
a way to make that happen.

07:58.853 --> 08:01.690
Hey.

08:05.527 --> 08:07.529
We can't afford a wedding,
can we?

08:07.612 --> 08:09.030
No one can afford a wedding.
Not really.

08:09.114 --> 08:11.533
We can figure it out.

08:11.616 --> 08:13.618
No, I‐I need
to get back to reality.

08:13.702 --> 08:15.078
I... Work has been crazy.

08:15.161 --> 08:16.538
I had to miss three days
to be here.

08:16.621 --> 08:19.374
Andrea already wants
to fucking kill me.

08:19.457 --> 08:23.128
It's fine. We'll just...
we'll get married at city hall.

08:23.211 --> 08:25.213
Come on, Whitney. You've been
talking about having a wedding

08:25.296 --> 08:26.715
in this house since
before you were in braces.

08:26.798 --> 08:28.133
I already found a red‐eye
that we can get on tonight.

08:28.216 --> 08:30.135
It has seats available.

08:30.218 --> 08:32.095
Give me six hours.

08:32.178 --> 08:33.513
Okay? Let's at least try.

08:33.596 --> 08:36.224
Then if you still
want to go to city hall,

08:36.307 --> 08:37.808
then we'll go to city hall.

08:37.892 --> 08:40.477
Come on. Have you got a pen?

08:45.316 --> 08:47.652
Right.
What's the first thing?

08:47.736 --> 08:49.404
‐Um...
‐Tent.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.740
Okay, I just received
the last part of my advance,

08:51.823 --> 08:54.117
and I can't think of a better
thing to spend it on.

08:54.200 --> 08:55.410
‐Dad, no.
‐So that's that done.

08:55.493 --> 08:57.662
‐Next?
‐Dad, you don't get it.

08:57.746 --> 09:00.582
A‐A tent is no good if you don't
have things to put in it.

09:00.665 --> 09:02.917
Backyard weddings are so
expensive because you have

09:03.001 --> 09:06.546
to pay for every single
little thing. See?

09:07.047 --> 09:10.300
Okay.

09:10.383 --> 09:12.343
Let's start with plates.

09:14.179 --> 09:16.347
Well, this house
has got to have plenty of those.

09:16.431 --> 09:18.641
<i>I always hoped</i>

09:18.725 --> 09:21.269
your mother would inherit this,

09:21.352 --> 09:23.229
but she insists
on feeding you all

09:23.313 --> 09:25.690
from earthenware as if
she grew up on a riverbank.

09:25.774 --> 09:27.442
But no matter,

09:27.525 --> 09:29.277
because now it'll go to someone
who appreciates it.

09:29.360 --> 09:32.155
‐Thank you, Grandma.
‐This is helpful.

09:32.238 --> 09:33.948
Thanks. What's next?

09:34.032 --> 09:36.618
Oh, I have an appointment at
an East Hampton bridal boutique

09:36.701 --> 09:38.620
at two,
but it's crazy expensive.

09:38.703 --> 09:41.539
‐I think we should cancel it.
‐You don't have a dress yet?

09:41.623 --> 09:43.333
Perfect. Come on, let's go.

09:43.416 --> 09:44.216
Oh, Margaret,
can we borrow your car?

09:44.250 --> 09:47.128
Only if Whitney drives.

09:47.212 --> 09:49.297
‐Why?
‐Because the last time you drove

09:49.380 --> 09:51.800
a car in Montauk,
you killed Scott Lockhart.

10:01.059 --> 10:03.311
So, what do you want
to do about music?

10:03.394 --> 10:05.480
You want dancing, right?

10:05.563 --> 10:07.690
Honestly, I kind of wanted
a flash mob.

10:07.774 --> 10:10.193
‐What?
‐You know, a flash mob?

10:10.276 --> 10:12.821
It's, like, a surprise dance,
but everyone knows the steps.

10:12.904 --> 10:16.157
How could everybody know
the steps to a surprise dance?

10:16.241 --> 10:17.575
Because somebody teaches them
ahead of time,

10:17.659 --> 10:20.453
and it's like a... Never mind.

10:23.081 --> 10:24.833
Oh, look.

10:26.334 --> 10:27.961
We have to stop

10:28.044 --> 10:29.963
and see what they've done
to the Lobster Roll.

10:30.046 --> 10:30.922
No, Whit‐Whitney,
we don't have time.

10:31.005 --> 10:33.800
Yes, we do. Come on.
It'll be hilarious.

10:57.448 --> 10:58.908
Hi, we okay here?

11:02.537 --> 11:04.455
Not as friendly
as they used to be.

11:04.539 --> 11:06.207
Yeah.

11:10.837 --> 11:14.424
Hey, remember when Stacey
almost choked and Mom saved her?

11:14.507 --> 11:15.717
What?

11:15.800 --> 11:18.344
Yeah, you remember.
We were sitting right there,

11:18.428 --> 11:20.388
and Trevor and Stacey were
playing that game, and then

11:20.471 --> 11:21.806
Stacey put a marble
in her mouth.

11:21.890 --> 11:25.226
No, it wasn't, uh, it wasn't
your mom who saved her.

11:25.310 --> 11:27.478
It was, it was Alison.

11:27.562 --> 11:29.397
What?

11:29.480 --> 11:31.399
No, that's‐that's not
how I remember it at all.

11:31.482 --> 11:32.734
No, I'm pretty sure it was her.

11:32.817 --> 11:34.861
Stacey was choking
and Alison was right there.

11:40.742 --> 11:43.494
So, was that the day
you met Alison?

11:44.412 --> 11:46.706
Yeah, I think it was.

11:48.291 --> 11:50.793
So you bonded over the fact that
Stacey almost choked to death?

11:52.629 --> 11:53.630
Whitney, if you ever want
to talk about what happened

11:53.713 --> 11:55.715
‐between Alison and me...
‐Yeah.

11:55.798 --> 11:56.925
Sure. I do, actually. Go ahead.

12:00.053 --> 12:02.597
Well, there's not... I didn't
exactly have a prepared speech.

12:02.680 --> 12:03.806
‐But if you‐‐
‐Yeah. That's what I thought.

12:03.890 --> 12:04.474
No, I mean, if you want
to ask questions or‐‐

12:04.557 --> 12:07.560
- ‐Stop.
- ‐ Noah?

12:08.519 --> 12:10.063
Luisa, hi.

12:10.146 --> 12:11.648
‐Hey.
‐Hey, you remember Whitney,

12:11.731 --> 12:14.275
‐my daughter?
‐Yeah, of course. Uh...

12:14.359 --> 12:15.610
I babysat you one summer
at the Butlers'.

12:15.693 --> 12:17.278
I remember. Nice to see you.

12:17.362 --> 12:18.863
Yeah, we're in town planning
Whitney's wedding,

12:18.947 --> 12:20.448
if you can believe it.

12:20.531 --> 12:23.409
Cool. Congratulations.

12:23.493 --> 12:25.161
Thank you.

12:25.245 --> 12:27.372
So this is different.

12:27.455 --> 12:31.834
Yeah. It's officially in the
hands of the new owners now.

12:31.918 --> 12:34.337
I just came by to empty
a few things out of the office.

12:34.420 --> 12:36.172
Ah. End of an era.

12:36.256 --> 12:38.925
Yep.

12:40.843 --> 12:42.470
I have to get going.

12:42.553 --> 12:44.764
What's, uh, what's next for you?

12:44.847 --> 12:47.267
I'm going back to New York.

12:47.350 --> 12:48.309
‐Really?
‐Mm‐hmm.

12:48.393 --> 12:49.394
Wow.

12:49.477 --> 12:52.438
I can't believe you got Cole
to go to the city.

12:54.190 --> 12:55.942
We're separated, Noah.

12:56.025 --> 12:58.152
He and Joanie
are moving to Vermont.

12:58.236 --> 13:01.823
This afternoon, actually,
so I have to get going.

13:01.906 --> 13:02.991
Congratulations on
your wedding. Good luck.

13:06.744 --> 13:08.955
I'll be right back.

13:09.038 --> 13:10.039
No, Dad, she doesn't
want to talk to us.

13:14.252 --> 13:15.670
Hey, Luisa.

13:15.753 --> 13:17.171
I'm sorry
if I offended you there.

13:17.255 --> 13:20.174
‐I had no idea.
‐It's fine.

13:20.258 --> 13:21.843
That's terrible
about you and Cole.

13:21.926 --> 13:25.096
Well, the writing
was on the wall, wasn't it?

13:25.179 --> 13:28.850
Look, I was wondering, have you
any idea when they're leaving?

13:28.933 --> 13:31.728
‐Why?
‐'Cause I want to see Joanie.

13:31.811 --> 13:33.980
You can't just waltz
in and out of her life

13:34.063 --> 13:36.024
‐when it's convenient.
‐I know that. I know that.

13:36.107 --> 13:39.319
I raised her as my own for
two years. I care about her.

13:39.402 --> 13:40.320
Noah, I don't feel like getting

13:40.403 --> 13:42.363
‐in the middle of this.
‐No, I understand.

13:42.447 --> 13:44.032
If you could just tell me
when they're leaving,

13:44.115 --> 13:46.075
then I can swing by, and if Cole
doesn't want me to see her,

13:46.159 --> 13:47.660
that's fine, I just,
I don't want her to think

13:47.744 --> 13:49.162
I just disappeared.

13:50.997 --> 13:52.248
They're leaving at five.

13:52.331 --> 13:53.875
Thanks.

13:55.626 --> 13:57.920
I'm sorry about
how it turned out here, and...

13:58.004 --> 13:59.005
I hope there are
good things ahead.

14:00.882 --> 14:03.843
Noah, I babysat your kids.

14:03.926 --> 14:06.137
My mother worked at your house.

14:06.220 --> 14:07.930
Don't pretend we're friends.

14:28.034 --> 14:30.870
‐Hey, can I get a menu, please?
‐You order on that.

14:33.581 --> 14:35.792
<i>♪ And death grabbed him
so quiet ♪</i>

14:35.875 --> 14:38.086
<i>♪ It didn't even make a sound ♪</i>

14:42.882 --> 14:45.927
<i>♪ As far as I could see
were dead leaves... ♪</i>

14:46.010 --> 14:48.596
Hey, just‐just pull over
right here, will you?

14:48.679 --> 14:50.765
‐ What, here?
‐Yeah. Just for a second.

